WHITE SPOT DISEASE - AUSTRALIA (02): (QUEENSLAND) PRAWNS, UPDATE
****************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 6 Dec 2016, 9:19 AM
Source: Undercurrent News [edited]
https://www.undercurrentnews.com/2016/12/05/ausie-shrimp-farm-locked-down-as-whitespot-confirmed/


A Queensland, Australia, shrimp farm has been ordered to place movement controls on its shrimp after test results confirmed a case of white spot disease (WSD).

The order came in from the Queensland Department of Agriculture and Fisheries. Jim Thompson, chief biosecurity officer of Biosecurity Queensland, said samples from the farm were sent to the Australian Animal Health Laboratory in Geelong and he had received confirmation of positive results for WSD.

"WSD is a viral infection that affects all crustaceans," said Thompson. "Australia is considered free of the virus and this is the 1st confirmed case we've had in an aquaculture setting."

"Infected prawns [shrimp] do not pose any human health risk, and there is no suggestion that any product currently on the market is in any way affected." "Industry has been notified and Biosecurity Queensland is on site working closely with the farm operators to ensure the necessary biosecurity processes are followed, including completely destocking the site."

In addition, all movement of water from the farm has been stopped while the affected ponds are treated to minimize any risk of spread, he said.

"As part of our ongoing investigation into the possible source of the infection, we are conducting surveillance on other similar operations in the area." The case appears to be an isolated one, and will have no impact on the supplies of shrimp for the holiday season, he added.

Agriculture and Fisheries Minister Bill Byrne said he had authorized the response after being briefed on the test results.

Biosecurity Queensland is asking shrimp farmers to monitor their stock and report any concerns.

