[The following information is quoted from the Australian Government's "National pest & disease outbreaks" website available at, http://www.outbreak.gov.au/current-responses-to-outbreaks/white-spot-disease:

"White spot disease, which is a highly contagious viral disease of prawns, has been detected on a prawn farm south of Brisbane, in South East Queensland. White spot disease is caused by a virus known as white spot syndrome virus. The disease, and the virus that causes it were both exotic to Australia, and pose a significant threat to the Australia's crustacean industries.

"The disease causes prawn mortality but does not pose a threat to human health or food safety. Prawns from this farm will not enter any domestic or international markets, nor will they be processed for human consumption.

"Officers from the Queensland Department of Agriculture and Fisheries have attended the farm and put in place enhanced biosecurity measures and movement controls.

"Disease signs were first noticed by the farmer on 22 Nov 2016. Queensland's Biosecurity Sciences Laboratory detected white spot syndrome virus on [30 Nov 2016]. Samples were also sent to the Australian Animal Health Laboratory in Geelong, and it confirmed white spot disease on 1 December. [See ProMED-mail posting 20161202.4670306. - Mod.CRD]

"It is not yet known how the disease got onto the farm but the potential source of the disease is being investigated. At this stage there is no indication that the disease has spread beyond this particular farm.

"The national Aquatic Consultative Committee on Emergency Animal Diseases has met and agreed on response activities moving forward, with the aim of eradicating the disease from the farm. National response arrangements are in place to respond to white spot disease, including AQUAVETPLAN which sets out agreed destruction, disposal and decontamination activities.

- AQUAVETPLAN - Disease Strategy Manual - White Spot disease http://www.agriculture.gov.au/animal/aquatic/aquavetplan/white-spot

"The Queensland Department of Agriculture and Fisheries will also conduct surveillance to determine the extent of the disease". - Mod.CRD

